Shared Qs (030)


  1. Question

    Let \(x(t)\) represent a train’s position as a function of time. For some train during some period of time, the position can be modeled with a quadratic function.

    \[x(t) = 6t^2+5t-10\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a linear function in time, which depends on the acceleration \(a\) and the initial velocity \(v_0\).

    \[v(t) ~=~ at+v_0\]

    Determine \(a\) and \(v_0\).

    • \(a=\)
    • \(v_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(6(t+h)^2+5(t+h)-10\right)-\left(6t^2+5t-10\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6(t+h)^2+5(t+h)-10-6t^2-5t+10}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6(t^2+2th+h^2)+5(t+h)-10-6t^2-5t+10}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6t^2+12th+6h^2+5t+5h-10-6t^2-5t+10}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{12th+6h^2+5h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(12t+6h+5)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(12t+6h+5\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~12t+6\cdot 0+5\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~12t+5\]

    So, \(a=12\) and \(v_0=5\).



  2. Question

    Let \(x(t)\) represent a train’s position as a function of time. For some train during some period of time, the position can be modeled with a quadratic function.

    \[x(t) = 4t^2-8t+5\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a linear function in time, which depends on the acceleration \(a\) and the initial velocity \(v_0\).

    \[v(t) ~=~ at+v_0\]

    Determine \(a\) and \(v_0\).

    • \(a=\)
    • \(v_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(4(t+h)^2-8(t+h)+5\right)-\left(4t^2-8t+5\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{4(t+h)^2-8(t+h)+5-4t^2+8t-5}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{4(t^2+2th+h^2)-8(t+h)+5-4t^2+8t-5}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{4t^2+8th+4h^2-8t-8h+5-4t^2+8t-5}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{8th+4h^2-8h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(8t+4h-8)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(8t+4h-8\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~8t+4\cdot 0-8\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~8t-8\]

    So, \(a=8\) and \(v_0=-8\).

  4. Question

    Let \(x(t)\) represent a train’s position as a function of time. For some train during some period of time, the position can be modeled with a quadratic function.

    \[x(t) = -10t^2-9t-4\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a linear function in time, which depends on the acceleration \(a\) and the initial velocity \(v_0\).

    \[v(t) ~=~ at+v_0\]

    Determine \(a\) and \(v_0\).

    • \(a=\)
    • \(v_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-10(t+h)^2-9(t+h)-4\right)-\left(-10t^2-9t-4\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-10(t+h)^2-9(t+h)-4+10t^2+9t+4}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-10(t^2+2th+h^2)-9(t+h)-4+10t^2+9t+4}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-10t^2-20th-10h^2-9t-9h-4+10t^2+9t+4}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-20th-10h^2-9h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(-20t-10h-9)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(-20t-10h-9\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~-20t-10\cdot 0-9\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~-20t-9\]

    So, \(a=-20\) and \(v_0=-9\).



  5. Question

  6. Question

    A train’s position \(x(t)\) as a function of time \(t\) can be modeled with a cubic function. \[x(t) = -5t^3-10t^2-2t-7\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a quadratic function in time.

    \[v(t) ~=~ pt^2+qt+r\]

    Determine \(p\) and \(q\) and \(r\).

    • \(p=\)
    • \(q=\)
    • \(r=\)

    The acceleration is the derivative of velocity.

    \[a(t) = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{v(t+h)-v(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(a(t)\) is a linear function in time.

    \[a(t)~=~jt+a_0\]

    where \(j\) is the jerk and \(a_0\) is the initial acceleration.

    Determine \(j\) and \(a_0\).

    • \(j=\)
    • \(a_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-5(t+h)^3-10(t+h)^2-2(t+h)-7\right)-\left(-5t^3-10t^2-2t-7\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-5(t+h)^3-10(t+h)^2-2(t+h)-7+5t^3+10t^2+2t+7}{h}\]

    Apply the rules of binomial expansion.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-5(t^3+3t^2h+3th^2+h^3)-10(t^2+2th+h^2)-2(t+h)-7+5t^3+10t^2+2t+7}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-5t^3-15t^2h-15th^2-5h^3-10t^2-20th-10h^2-2t-2h-7+5t^3+10t^2+2t+7}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15t^2h-15th^2-5h^3-20th-10h^2-2h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-15t^2-15th-5h^2-20t-10h-2\right)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(-15t^2-15th-5h^2-20t-10h-2\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~-15t^2-15t\cdot 0-5\cdot 0^2-20t-10\cdot 0-2\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~-15t^2-20t-2\]

    So, \(p=-15\) and \(q=-20\) and \(r=-2\).

    Acceleration function

    \[a(t) = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{v(t+h)-v(t)}{h}\]

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-15(t+h)^2-20(t+h)-2\right)-\left(-15t^2-20t-2\right)}{h}\]

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15(t+h)^2-20(t+h)-2+15t^2+20t+2}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15(t^2+2th+h^2)-20(t+h)-2+15t^2+20t+2}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15t^2-30th-15h^2-20t-20h-2+15t^2+20t+2}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-30th-15h^2-20h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(-30t-15h-20)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(-30t-15h-20\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[a(t)~=~-30t-15\cdot 0-20\]

    Simplify.

    \[a(t)~=~-30t-20\]

    So, \(j=-30\) and \(a_0=-20\).

  8. Question

    A train’s position \(x(t)\) as a function of time \(t\) can be modeled with a cubic function. \[x(t) = 2t^3-7t^2+5t+8\]

    • \(a_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2(t+h)^3-7(t+h)^2+5(t+h)+8-2t^3+7t^2-5t-8}{h}\]

    Apply the rules of binomial expansion.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2(t^3+3t^2h+3th^2+h^3)-7(t^2+2th+h^2)+5(t+h)+8-2t^3+7t^2-5t-8}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2t^3+6t^2h+6th^2+2h^3-7t^2-14th-7h^2+5t+5h+8-2t^3+7t^2-5t-8}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(6t^2+6th+2h^2-14t-7h+5\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~6t^2+6t\cdot 0+2\cdot 0^2-14t-7\cdot 0+5\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~6t^2-14t+5\]

    So, \(p=6\) and \(q=-14\) and \(r=5\).

    Acceleration function

    \[a(t) = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{v(t+h)-v(t)}{h}\]

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(6(t+h)^2-14(t+h)+5\right)-\left(6t^2-14t+5\right)}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6(t^2+2th+h^2)-14(t+h)+5-6t^2+14t-5}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6t^2+12th+6h^2-14t-14h+5-6t^2+14t-5}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

  16. Question

    First, we can prove that if \(f(t) = m(t)+n(t)\) then \(f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\). In other words, the derivative of a sum equals the sum of the derivatives. Or, in other words, differentiation is linear. The proof follows.

    \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(t+h)-f(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)+n(t+h)\right)-\left(m(t)+n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)-m(t)\right)+\left(n(t+h)-n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\left(\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\right)\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\]

    Also, if \(g(t) = at^b\) then \(g'(t) = (ab)t^{b-1}\). In other words, the derivative of a power function is found by multiplying the coefficient by the power and then reducing the power by one.

    Let \(f(t)\) be a function defined below: \[f(t)~=~7.2t^{9.1}+4.1t^{2.5}\]

    Using the rules above, find \(f'(0.44)\). The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    Don’t use the definition of a derivative. We get to use the shortcuts now.

    \[f'(t) = (7.2\cdot 9.1)t^{9.1-1}+(4.1\cdot 2.5)t^{2.5-1}\]

    Simplify.

    \[f'(t) = (65.52)t^{8.1}+(10.25)t^{1.5}\]

    Now, use the given value of \(t\).

    \[f'(0.44) = (65.52)(0.44)^{8.1}+(10.25)(0.44)^{1.5}\]

    Plug the expression into a calculator.

    \[(65.52)(0.44)^{8.1}+(10.25)(0.44)^{1.5} = 3.0763848\]

    So,

    \[f'(0.44)~=~3.0763848\]


    Above, the black curve is \(y=f(t)\) and the blue (tangent) line is \(y=f'(0.44)\cdot(t-0.44)+f(0.44)\), written in point-slope form. The two intersect at point \((0.44,f(0.44))\). The slope of the tangent line equals \(f'(0.44)\), which equals 3.0763848.

  18. Question

    First, we can prove that if \(f(t) = m(t)+n(t)\) then \(f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\). In other words, the derivative of a sum equals the sum of the derivatives. Or, in other words, differentiation is linear. The proof follows.

    \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(t+h)-f(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)+n(t+h)\right)-\left(m(t)+n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)-m(t)\right)+\left(n(t+h)-n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\left(\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\right)\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\]

    Also, if \(g(t) = at^b\) then \(g'(t) = (ab)t^{b-1}\). In other words, the derivative of a power function is found by multiplying the coefficient by the power and then reducing the power by one.

    Let \(f(t)\) be a function defined below: \[f(t)~=~8.9t^{4.3}+2t^{7.5}\]

    Using the rules above, find \(f'(0.5)\). The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    Don’t use the definition of a derivative. We get to use the shortcuts now.

    \[f'(t) = (8.9\cdot 4.3)t^{4.3-1}+(2\cdot 7.5)t^{7.5-1}\]

    Simplify.

    \[f'(t) = (38.27)t^{3.3}+(15)t^{6.5}\]

    Now, use the given value of \(t\).

    \[f'(0.5) = (38.27)(0.5)^{3.3}+(15)(0.5)^{6.5}\]

    Plug the expression into a calculator.

    \[(38.27)(0.5)^{3.3}+(15)(0.5)^{6.5} = 4.0513406\]

    So,

    \[f'(0.5)~=~4.0513406\]


    Above, the black curve is \(y=f(t)\) and the blue (tangent) line is \(y=f'(0.5)\cdot(t-0.5)+f(0.5)\), written in point-slope form. The two intersect at point \((0.5,f(0.5))\). The slope of the tangent line equals \(f'(0.5)\), which equals 4.0513406.

  21. Question

    Consider the polynomial function below. \[f(x)=-8x^{5}+10x^{4}\]

    Determine \[f''(-0.24)\]. The tolerance is \(\pm0.01\).


    Solution

    Use the differentiation rules. Specifically the power rule along with the sum and constant multiple rules.

    \[f(x)=-8x^{5}+10x^{4}\] \[f'(x)=-40x^{4}+40x^{3}\] \[f''(x)=-160x^{3}+120x^{2}\]

    Plug in \(x=-0.24\).

    \[f''(-0.24) ~=~ -160\cdot(-0.24)^{3}+120\cdot(-0.24)^{2}\] \[f''(-0.24) ~\approx~ 9.12\]

  26. Question

    A bucket initially holds 8.1 liters of water. A hole is punched into the bottom of the bucket, so water leaks out following Torricelli’s law. Below, volume is shown as a function of time, where \(t\) in in minutes.

    \[V(t)~=~1t^2-5.7t+8.1\]

    How fast (in liters per minute) is water leaving the bucket at \(t=2.23\) minutes? (Tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\) liters per minute.)


    Solution

    We were given the volume as a function of time.

    \[V(t) ~=~ 1t^2-5.7t+8.1\]

    Find the derivative of the volume function (with respect to time). Use the differentiation rules.

    \[V'(t) ~=~ (1\cdot 2)t^{2-1}+(-5.7\cdot 1)t^{1-1}\]

    \[V'(t) ~=~ 2t-5.7\]

    Plug the specified time \(t=2.23\) into the function.

    \[V'(2.23) ~=~ -1.24\]

    So, when \(t=2.23\), water is leaving at a rate of 1.24 liters per minute.

  31. Question

    A human converts chemical energy (energy stored as ATP and carbohydrates) into gravitational potential energy by pedaling a bicycle up a hill. During a short burst, the amount of work (stored as potential energy), as a function of time, follows the polynomial expression below, where energy (\(E\)) is in joules and time (\(t\)) is in seconds. \[E(t) ~=~ 1.79t^4-48.18t^3+364.61t^2+44.69t\]


    For your reference, 4184 joules is 1 kilocalorie (and in the US, in regards to food, we call 1 kilocalorie a “calorie”… just to be as confused as possible).

    Power is the rate of energy per time. In this case, we will measure power in watts, where 1 watt equals 1 joule per second. A human burns 100 watts as basal metabolism. Walking burns an additional 30 watts. A professional cyclist can maintain 400 watts of output while racing (see Human Power). A typical college-aged student can output 1000 watts for a few seconds. Usain Bolt’s record sprint required a burst of 2500 watts (about 3.5 horsepower) for part of the sprint. Throughout history, a laborer would average about 100 watts above basal metabolism (see Vaclav Smil).

    Anyway, at \(t=5.5\) seconds, what is the power output of the human in watts? The tolerance is \(\pm 1\) watt.


    Solution

    Find the derivative.

    \[E'(t) ~=~ 7.16t^3-144.54t^2+729.22t+44.69\]

    Plug in \(t=5.5\) seconds.

    \[E'(5.5) ~=~ 874.31\]


    So, the answer is 874 J/s or 874 watts.

  36. Question

    The graph of \(y=f(x)\) is shown below. Also, at \(x=3\), a tangent line is drawn.


    The tangent line can be used to determine the instantaneous rate of change of \(f(x)\) at \(x=3\).

    Please estimate \(f'(3)\) within the nearest hundredth. This could also be notated as \(\left.\frac{df(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=3}\) or as \(\frac{df}{dx}(3)\). For more, see wikipedia’s article on notation for differentiation.


    Solution

    Notice the tangent line intersects \(f(x)\) at point \((3,1)\). From there, follow the red line until you get to another point with integer coordinates.


    The slope of the tangent line is found with “rise over run”.

    \[m ~=~ \frac{3}{4}\]

    \[m ~=~ 0.75\]

    So, the equation of the tangent line in point-slope form is \(y=0.75(x-(3))+(1)\). More importantly for this question, the slope of the tangent line equals the instantaneous rate of change of the function, which equals the derivative at \(x=3\). In other words, \[f'(3) ~=~ 0.75\]

    \[\left.\frac{df(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=3} ~=~ 0.75\]

    \[\frac{df}{dx}(3) ~=~ 0.75\]

    \[\frac{df}{dx}(-2) ~=~ 0.3333333\]



  39. Question

    The graph of \(y=f(x)\) is shown below. Also, at \(x=1\), a tangent line is drawn.


    The tangent line can be used to determine the instantaneous rate of change of \(f(x)\) at \(x=1\).

    Please estimate \(f'(1)\) within the nearest hundredth. This could also be notated as \(\left.\frac{df(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=1}\) or as \(\frac{df}{dx}(1)\). For more, see wikipedia’s article on notation for differentiation.


    Solution

    Notice the tangent line intersects \(f(x)\) at point \((1,1)\). From there, follow the red line until you get to another point with integer coordinates.


    The slope of the tangent line is found with “rise over run”.

    \[m ~=~ \frac{1}{5}\]

    \[m ~=~ 0.2\]

    So, the equation of the tangent line in point-slope form is \(y=0.2(x-(1))+(1)\). More importantly for this question, the slope of the tangent line equals the instantaneous rate of change of the function, which equals the derivative at \(x=1\). In other words, \[f'(1) ~=~ 0.2\]

    \[\left.\frac{df(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=1} ~=~ 0.2\]

    \[\frac{df}{dx}(1) ~=~ 0.2\]
